Scenes from a dying web

Casey Newton

Feb 5, 2024 — 12 min read

From Arc Search to Quora, the future is coming into focus — and there’s reason to worry

I.

If the web is going to die, it won’t die all at once. 

Instead, it will die a little bit at a time: with a venerable old publication being folded into another; with a well funded upstart sputtering into nothing in under a year; with a subscription business abandoned after it struggled to find enough good writers to keep it going.

The death of digital media has many causes, including the ineptitude of its funders and managers. But today I want to talk about another potential rifle on the firing squad: generative artificial intelligence, which in its capacity to strip-mine the web and repurpose it as an input for search engines threatens to remove one of the few pillars of revenue remaining for publishers.

This is a story that is less about how the web is used today and more about how it is viewed by the tech platforms now searching it for fresh opportunities. It’s a reminder that the future of the web depends on what products get built for it. On what labor is funded, and what labor is not. 

Last week, a startup called the Browser Company released a new app called Arc Search. For a few years now, the company has been working to devise a more useful web browser. And while none of the tools it has developed so far have given me cause to abandon Chrome, by default I root for anyone who spends their time and energy working to improve the open web. 

Opening the Arc Search app for the first time last week, though, I experienced a rare emotion: a kind of revulsion at the app’s mere existence, and at what it portends. When you enter a query in the app, Arc Search uses APIs from OpenAI and others to “read the web” for you and build a page that attempts to answer your question in full. When I asked about King Charles’ cancer diagnosis today, Arc Search sourced information from six websites, synthesized it, and gave me an accurate, bullet-pointed rundown of the little that is known so far. 

Arc is not alone in exploring this new, more extractive form of web search. Perplexity, which was profiled last week by my podcast co-host Kevin Roose, offers a similar generative AI summary based on news articles. So does ChatGPT. 

This is clearly a better user experience for those seeking information about the king. Rather than click on one or more stories, navigate various ads and pop-up windows, and scan for information, Arc Search and its peers grab the most valuable bits and serve them to you without interruption.

To deliver that user experience, though, Arc Search relied on stories from NBC, CNN, USA Today, and others. Those stories were written by journalists who are paid largely through the advertising revenue on the web pages that readers might have otherwise visited. A huge number of the journalism jobs that still remain depend on the pipeline that delivers search queries to web pages.

To its credit, Arc Search links to its sources somewhat prominently. (Much more prominently, for example, than OpenAI, which puts a tiny linked quotation mark in brackets at the end of queries that offers no indication of what the source is and would require surgical precision to click on even if you wanted to.)

Still, the point of apps like Arc Search is that you should never have to visit the links at all. In Arc’s vision of the internet, all the labor that makes up the web is abstracted away into an input. And, best of all for a small startup, it’s a free input. You have to pay OpenAI for the APIs, sure. But it’s a small price to pay to harness the collective labor of thousands of people whom you will never have to compensate, even as you eventually figure out your own way to monetize it through ads and subscriptions.

To be fair, Arc Search didn’t invent this kind of scraping and remixing. Google itself has long offered excerpts and snippets of web pages as part of search results, and its own Search Generative Experience product moves even further toward the place where Arc and its peers have already arrived. 

On Monday afternoon I spoke with Josh Miller, co-founder and CEO of the Browser Company, to ask how he thought about these issues. Miller previously founded the conversation platform Branch, which he sold to Facebook, and later served as the director of product at the White House. In addition to running the Browser Company, he is also a board member of Patreon.

Miller told me that Arc Search had arisen from his frustration with traditional web search. While traveling to Finland, he said, a flight attendant had told him that tea cost $6 but he could have water or blueberry juice for free. Why was the airline giving away free blueberry juice, he wondered? Miller said he struggled to get the right answer with a traditional search, and hoped to get a better one with generative AI. (When I ran the queries in both Arc Search and Google today, the correct answer came up at the top of both apps. Blueberry juice is the signature drink of Finnair, and is meant to invoke Finnish cuisine.)

Miller told me that generative AI represents a chance to shake up the stagnant oligopoly that runs much of the web today — but acknowledged that it was not clear how writers would be paid in the future. “It completely upends the economics of publishing on the internet,” he said. 

Arc Search was conceived as a kind of side project for the Browser Company, Miller told me, and as such he had not put much thought into the second-order implications of a world where search queries no longer result in outbound clicks. 

“The reason we didn't talk about our ideas related to web pages and creator monetization of the future (in the video) is because we don't have all the answers yet!” Miller wrote on X, in response to a developer who asked him about Arc Search’s economics. “Nobody does. It's all too new. And it felt important to be honest.”

He added: “But promise I'm thinking deeply about this conundrum. It's so important for everything from our web to our democracy.”

Like Miller, I wish Google had less power over the web. At the same time, Google at least has a theory of how the web can be funded: it will deliver clicks to publishers, and publishers will monetize those clicks via ads. (Ads which Google also sells, of course.)

This is far from an ideal system. The number of working journalists continues to shrink, while Google continues to print money. And it seems clear that Google will gradually replace as much of its current search product with generative AI as it can. How can it not? Its competitors all already have.

But as unsatisfying as the status quo may be, it still represents a marked improvement on the world predicted by Arc Search. The Google of today is organized around the principle that it is necessary and even enjoyable to visit websites. The search engines of tomorrow are premised on the idea that it would be far better and more enjoyable not to.

II.

As less of the web is created by professional journalists, what will replace it? 

In Quora, we have a fascinating case study.

The question-and-answer site arose in 2010 as an effort to democratize publishing by soliciting experts of every kind to tackle whatever questions users might pose to them. Founded by a couple of ex-Facebook employees, Quora found initial success by getting people who would never start their own websites to publish occasional posts without the pressure that would come with running a blog. In time it ran some of the first experiments with letting bloggers make money from their work on the platform. 

Relatively soon afterward, its place in the ecosystem was eclipsed by Medium, which would then go on to be eclipsed by Substack. Quora faded into the background, gradually transforming into the kind of braindead content farm that it had once sought to replace. By 2019, Vox was writing that Quora had been all but forgotten, even as it still somehow got investors to value it at $2 billion. 

Fast forward five years, and what is Quora? Nitish Pahwa wrote about the site in its current state on Friday at Slate:

Today’s Quora, however, hardly meshes with those utopian aims. The once-beloved forum is now home to a never-ending avalanche of meaningless, repetitive sludge, filled with bizarre, nonsensical, straight-up hateful, and A.I.–generated entries along with a slurry of all-caps non-questions like “OMG! KING CHARLES SHOCK the WORLD with ROYAL BAN ON PRINCE HARRY AND MEGHAN MARKLE. SAD?” (The answer to this “question,” which garnered about 7 million views, links to a bizarre, barely functional royals-watching website called red-carpett.com.) Whereas once you could Google a question about current events and find links to thoughtful Quora answers near the top of the results, you’re now more likely to come upon, say, a bunch of folks asking … whether the consistently racist Donald Trump is, in fact, racist. Or, maybe, the featured Google snippet will tell you that eggs can melt, thanks to a nonsense Quora answer caught in the search crawler.

Despite that sorry state of affairs, though, Andreessen Horowitz just put another $75 million into the company. What gives?

It turns out the money will not be spent in an effort to revive Quora. Rather, it will be spent on Poe: a kind of browser for chatbots that gives users a single place to talk to chatbots from OpenAI, Anthropic, and others. It’s not all that different from Arc Search, really: just another front end for various chatbot APIs. 

It feels telling that Quora CEO Adam D’Angelo once sought to build a community for writers, and has now all but abandoned that vision in favor of a marketplace for robot assistants. How much more attractive must that pitch have been to investors — this vision of a Q&A product in which humans no longer need to be compensated, or even consulted, at all. 

I understand that everything I’m writing about today can be dismissed as an experiment. But all the time now, in ways big and small, tech platforms are telling us what they expect the future to look like. And it is not a world in which journalists or almost anyone else now employed in writing or creating has any real role to play aside from training the models that their makers are betting will one day replace them.  

To the extent that journalists have a role to play in the web of the future, it is one they will have to invent for themselves. Use Arc Search, or Perplexity, or Poe, and it is clear that there is no platform coming to save journalism. And there are an increasingly large number of platforms who seem intent on killing it.

Governing

  • The number of organizations participating in AI-related lobbying surged by 185 percent in 2023, growing to 450 from 158 in the prior year. As expected, companies include ByteDance, Tesla and Nvidia. (Hayden Field / CNBC)
    • Chinese companies ByteDance and Shein are boosting their lobbying efforts in the US as they seek to minimize business effects resulting from US-China tensions. (Ryotaro Yamada / Nikkei Asia)
  • EU countries unanimously reached a deal on the Artificial Intelligence Act, a landmark law that will see stricter rules on high-risk AI tech, transparency obligations, and bans on some AI applications. (Gian Volpicelli / Politico)
  • The UK’s Intellectual Property Office was unable to produce guidance on material used for AI training, after industry executives reportedly could not agree on a voluntary code of practice. (Daniel Thomas and Cristina Criddle / Financial Times)
  • The Taylor Swift non-consensual deepfakes were a result of a challenge by 4chan users to bypass Microsoft's safety mechanisms, an analysis found. (Margi Murphy / Bloomberg)
  • The Oversight Board says a misleadingly edited video of Joe Biden can stay on Facebook, but urged Meta to update its manipulated media policy as the 2024 elections approach. (Karissa Bell / Engadget)
  • A worker at an international finance firm was duped into paying $25 million to scammers who used deepfakes to pose as the company’s chief financial officer and several other employees in a video call. As Renee DiResta noted over on Threads, this one reads like a sci-fi movie. (Heather Chen and Kathleen Magramo / CNN)
  • Some kids and activists are speaking out against the Kids Online Safety Bill and how it might violate First Amendment rights and result in more sensitive data collection instead of its stated goal of protecting minors. (Taylor Lorenz / Washington Post)
  • A federal judge is allowing a class action lawsuit by Apple customers who say the company is monopolizing the iPhone app market by banning non-App Store purchases.  (Jonathan Stempel / Reuters)
    • Phil Schiller, who runs Apple’s App Store, says third party app stores could present more risks to consumers because of different rules in different marketplaces. (Michael Grothaus / Fast Company)
  • A website called OnlyFake claims it uses “neural networks” to generate photos of fake IDs, but it poses wide-ranging risks from bank fraud to money laundering. (Joseph Cox / 404 Media)
  • Sexual assaults in virtual reality are rapidly increasing, and police departments are starting to take notice. But prosecution of these assaults are difficult, experts say. (Naomi Nix / Washington Post)
  • US consumers are increasingly getting most of their news from social media over television, a new report shows. (Marketing Dive)

Industry

  • Multiple board members at Tesla and other Musk companies have close financial ties and have done illegal drugs with Elon Musk. Another outstanding story from the Journal on this subject. (Kirsten Grind, Emily Glazer, Rebecca Elliott and Coulter Jones / The Wall Street Journal)
  • Meta saw a $197 billion surge in its market capitalization last week, the biggest in stock market history. (Subrat Patnaik / Bloomberg)
  • Meta is setting itself apart in the AI arms race, choosing to release its Llama offerings free and mostly open source, and with a higher percentage of women in top AI leadership positions. (Reed Albergotti / Semafor)
  • Developers and customers are upset by the closure of Meta’s Facebook Groups API, saying certain aspects of their businesses, including marketing, will be impacted. (Sarah Perez / TechCrunch)
  • TikTok is now boosting views for creators that post more horizontal, long-form videos over one minute in length. (Taylor Lorenz / Washington Post)
  • Universal Music Group and TikTok are about to find out who needs who more, as music from top artists get pulled off the app. (Lucas Shaw / Bloomberg)
  • Apple’s Vision Pro launched in the US, and Tim Cook says the value consumer gets justifies the high price tag. (Alex Koller / CNBC)
    • Cook appeared at Apple’s Fifth Avenue flagship store in Manhattan as crowds lined up to pick up their headsets. (Mark Gurman and Caroline Hyde / Bloomberg)
    • The Disney+ app on the Vision Pro is a big bet on spatial computing, as it’s one of the only streaming apps tailor-made for VisionOS. (Harry McCracken / Fast Company)
    • YouTube says a Vision Pro app is on the roadmap, despite previous statements declining to let their iPad app run on the headset. (Nilay Patel / The Verge)
  • Apple quadrupled the number of miles tested in its secretive autonomous vehicle last year, compared to 2022. (Aarian Marshall / WIRED)
  • Amazon and UK publisher Reach are partnering for customer data in online advertising, to compensate for the loss of cookies. (Daniel Thomas / Financial Times)
  • Microsoft is partnering with news startup Semafor to sponsor a breaking news feed named “Signals” that uses research provided by its AI chatbot. (Anna Nicolaou / Financial Times)
  • Despite a booming US economy, companies like Google, Microsoft and Amazon are still laying off employees, and tech jobs may be becoming less attractive. (Gerrit De Vynck, Danielle Abril and Caroline O’Donavan / Washington Post)
  • A small accounting change that extended the estimated working life of servers added $10 billion to Microsoft, Google, Meta, and Amazon’s profits. (Tabby Kinder, Camilla Hodgson and Cristina Criddle / Financial Times)
  • Across tech earnings, executives are telling investors that they have to spend money to make money in AI. (Hayden Field / CNBC)
    • Also from earnings: the digital ad market seems to be rebounding, as Alphabet, Meta, and Amazon see growth in ads. (Jonathan Vanian / CNBC)
  • Joe Rogan’s new Spotify deal is reportedly worth $250 million, and will allow the show to be distributed broadly. A Spotify exclusive no more. (Anne Steele / The Wall Street Journal)
  • Reddit reportedly picked the New York Stock Exchange to make its IPO debut. (Nicholas Megaw and Hannah Murphy / Financial Times)
    • Reddit’s revenue reportedly rose by more than 20 percent ahead of its IPO, but the company is still not profitable. (Amy Or / Bloomberg)
  • Seven months after Reddit changed its prices and rules for API access, some developers are finding workarounds, some have shut down, and some moved to other platforms. (Scharon Harding / Ars Technica)
  • Snap says it plans to lay off 10 percent of its global workforce, around 500 employees, in a reorganization. (Rohan Goswami / CNBC)
  • Creatives like writers and musicians are facing mounting pressure to become social media influencers in their own right to get people to pay attention to their art. (Rebecca Jennings / Vox)
